Watap , watape , wattap , or wadab ([/wəˈtɑːp/](/Help:IPA/English) or [/wæˈtɑːp/](/Help:IPA/English)) is the [thread](/Thread_(yarn)) and [cordage](/Rope) used by the [Native Americans of the United States](/Native_Americans_of_the_United_States) and [First Nations peoples of Canada](/First_Nations_in_Canada) to sew together sheets and panels of [birchbark](/Birchbark). The term originates from the [Algonquian](/Algonquian_languages) language family, but the material was employed by virtually all Indigenous groups inhabiting the range of the [paper birch](/Betula_papyrifera) across North America. Historically, watap cordage was produced from the robust aerial or subterranean roots of a selection of [conifers](/Conifers), most notably the [white spruce](/Picea_glauca), the [black spruce](/Picea_mariana), and the [Northern whitecedar](/Thuja_occidentalis). These root fibers possess a remarkable [tensile strength](/Tensile_strength) that enables them to endure the stresses of repeated stitching and exposure to moisture. In a conventional production sequence, the harvested roots undergo debarking, prolonged immersion in water to soften the tissue, followed by either [steaming](/Steaming) or [boiling](/Boil) to increase pliability before they can be fashioned into [sewing](/Sewing) cords. The processed roots may be utilized whole as sturdy cords, or they may be split into finer strands suitable for [twine](/Twine), depending on the intended application and the desired balance between flexibility and durability. This methodology, documented in ethnographic sources, reflects a sophisticated understanding of material science that was passed down through generations of Indigenous artisans. &#91;1&#93;

== Uses ==

Sewn birchbark panels were a cornerstone of material culture among the native peoples of the Upper Great Lakes, serving both functional and ceremonial purposes. The most celebrated application was the construction of lightweight [canoe](/Canoe) hulls. Artisans would stitch together overlapping sheets of [birchbark](/Birchbark) using watap, then seal the seams with natural tree resin to achieve a degree of waterproofing that permitted extended voyages across the interior waterways. Beyond canoes, the same watap‑stitched bark could be fashioned into a variety of containers, including baskets, food‑storage pouches, and ceremonial vessels. Decorative motifs, often incised or painted, were incorporated into the stitching pattern, allowing each piece to convey clan identity or personal narrative. Moreover, the watap technique formed an integral component of the [Midewiwin](/Midewiwin) tradition, wherein sacred [birchbark scrolls](/Wiigwaasabak) were bound together with the same cordage to preserve knowledge, ceremonial instructions, and historical narratives. These scrolls, revered as mnemonic devices, underscore the cultural significance of watap as more than a mere utilitarian material. &#91;2&#93; &#91;3&#93;

== Linguistic heritage ==

The lexical item "watap" entered European linguistic records via [Canadian French](/Canadian_French), subsequently being borrowed directly into English and other colonial languages. Its ultimate etymological root lies in the [Cree](/Cree_language) word *watapiy*, a term that conveys the notion of a cord or strap. The pervasive use of the word across multiple Algonquian dialects testifies to the central role of birchbark craft within those societies and to the extensive distribution of the paper birch and associated coniferous species throughout their ancestral territories. The [Anishinaabe](/Anishinaabe) peoples, who share linguistic affinities with the Cree, also harvested and processed watap on a large scale, integrating it into both everyday objects and ritual artifacts. Linguistic analyses suggest that the term may have undergone phonological adaptation as it spread, yet its core semantic content remained stable. &#91;4&#93;

== Geography ==

Hydrologically, the region surrounding the [Grand Portage](/Grand_Portage_National_Monument) features a notable body of water traditionally known as Watap Lake (also called Watape Lake), together with a corresponding portage route that historically facilitated travel between [Lake Superior](/Lake_Superior) and the interior continental watershed. The strategic importance of this corridor was such that the international boundary between [Canada](/Canada) and the [United States of America](/United_States_of_America) today follows the exact line of the lake and its adjoining portage, a testament to the lasting geopolitical imprint of Indigenous trade routes. Additionally, a separate watercourse—Watab River in [Stearns County, Minnesota](/Stearns_County,_Minnesota), served as a historic demarcation line separating the [Dakota](/Sioux) peoples to the west from the [Ojibwa](/Ojibwa) peoples to the east, as delineated in the 1825 [First Treaty of Prairie du Chien](/First_Treaty_of_Prairie_du_Chien). These geographic features illustrate how natural landmarks were incorporated into treaty boundaries and continue to shape regional identities.

